This is high-quality remanufactured ammunition designed to perform to the standard of the Mk262 that Special Operations Forces favor over the SS109 ("Green Tip") currently use with line units.
 This ammo will reliably fragment and transfer maximum energy to the target at longer ranges (and from short barrels) than either SS109 (62 gr. steel core) or M193 (55 gr. full metal jacket) ammunition
 We load the Hornady 75 gr. boat tail hollow point bullet to a velocity of 2790 feet per second from an 18" barrel. Brass is military contract and we use a primer with a hard cup designed to minimize "slam fires" in the AR-15 series rifle.
 If you plan to reload, you'll love this ammo. We have swaged (not reamed) out the military primer crimp, and we have trimmed the brass during our process to 1.745" (max length is 1.760") so you should not need to trim for several firings.
 Please note: this ammunition is loaded to 5.56 NATO pressures and is designed for use in weapons with a 5.56 NATO or .223 Wylde chamber.
 Compare with Black Hills Remanufactured ("Blue Box") at $650 per 1,000 not including shipping!
 If you are interested in technical info such as headspace, neck tension, temperature sensitivity, terminal ballistics, or external ballistic data, please contact us! We love to talk about this stuff!
 Shipping via FedEx to lower 48 US states only. We've had customers in California receive their ammo in two days!
 (Note: Hornady and Remington do not endorse, and are not affiliated with this ammunition.)
 We are set up to accept payment via Venmo! This is a gun and ammo friendly electronic payment system. Feel free to contact us for credit card payment options.
 -QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS-
 What is the difference between your 55¢ per round ammo and the stuff I see everywhere else for 25¢-35¢ a shot?
 Let's look at two issues: 1- cost; 2- performance.
 -COST
 Ammo priced in the 25¢ per shot range is usually Wolf or Tula brand. Two significant difference exist between our ammo and the Tula and Wolf ammo. Tula and Wolf use steel cases and copper washed, steel jacketed bullets in their lower priced offerings.
 Cheaper, steel-cased ammunition is harder on your rifle's chamber than softer, more smooth functioning brass-cased ammunition like we use. Cheaper steel-jacketed bullets are harder on your barrel than copper-jacketed bullets like we use. In short, you will experience more malfunctions and will wear out your rifle more quickly with steel cases and steel bullets. Is the cost savings in ammunition worth the cost in wear and tear on your rifle?
 Well, that depends on how much your rifle cost eh? For an inexpensive "beater" or "truck gun" the cost savings in probably worth the trade off. In a rifle with an expensive high-quality barrel (or a cheap barrel that just shoots great!) probably not!
 Brass-cased, copper-jacketed bullets that you find in ammo at the 35¢ per shot range avoids the wear and tear problems of the ammo that uses steel in cases and bullets.
 -PERFORMANCE
 Reliability
 The second difference, (and this applies for cheap guns or fancy guns) is in how the ammunition performs. For hunting or defensive work, steel-cased ammo will almost certainly cause more malfunctions. This is fine for training ammo. In fact, clearing more malfunctions could even offer a training advantage! But for serious work, reliability is a must.
 Terminal Performance
 Aside from reliability is the issue of "terminal ballistics." Terminal ballistics refer to what happens when the bullet you chose hits the target you chose. The choice of bullet should match the choice of target. If your choice is paper or pop cans, terminal performance isn't an issue for you--shoot the cheap stuff, unless you're shooting at longer ranges where wind becomes an issue. (Longer, heavier bullets buck the wind better!)
 The vast majority of the ammo you see in the 35¢ per shot range uses either a 55 grain lead core, copper jacketed bullet or a 62 gr. bullet with a copper jacket and steel core. We use a 75 gr. lead core, copper jacketed bullet. To cut to the chase: the heavier 75 gr. bullet is much more likely to stop a bad guy or humanely harvest a game animal than the cheaper 55 gr. or 62 gr. bullet.
 Why?
 The 55 gr. and 62 gr. bullets are more likely to zip right through the target leaving a wound similar to a .22 long rifle bullet. The 75 gr. bullet reliably tumbles and fragments in the target to cause the wounding, blood loss, tissue and organ destruction so critical to putting the bad guy or animal out of action.A NOTE ON SHIPPING
I do not treat shipping as a profit center. I charge the rate I have to pay UPS or FedEx because USPS will not handle ammunition. I can ship you 1,000 rounds for only a little more than it costs to ship you 20 rounds.
 As shooters, we are all in this together. I want you to stock up on quality ammo at a great price, so I will do my best to suit your needs and circumstances. Contact me with any questions friends. I'm in this business WITH people like me, FOR people like me.
Thanks for being an armed citizen!
